<subSubSection id="2B090C43CA8ED0E4A6658420CC09796B" pageId="1" pageNumber="80" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="E1CB3577F940448417680B68036B2833" pageId="1" pageNumber="80">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="173DAB27BAF10872DAA807B133A4657A" pageId="1" pageNumber="80">
The diagnostic characters for the genus 
<taxonomicName id="65E8259DA0696070C5795ADF86DE05E5" authority="Duvivier, 1891" authorityName="Duvivier" authorityYear="1891" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Sikkimia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Sikkimia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="80" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Sikkimia</taxonomicName>
, as indicated by 
<bibRefCitation id="77ACC30F10129808364122C6069E12CB" author="Bezdek, J" journalOrPublisher="Genus" pageId="23" pageNumber="102" pagination="351 - 358" title="Yunomela Chen, 1964 and Vietocerus Lopatin, 2003, new synonyms of Sikkimia Duvivier, 1891 (Coleoptera: Chrysomelidae: Galerucinae)." volume="17" year="2006">
<normalizedToken id="E6C2C420EB7EADB503848AAFAA4AA8B3" originalValue="Bezděk">Bezdek</normalizedToken>
and Zhang (2006)
</bibRefCitation>
, are modified and extended as follows: body large (6.1-12.0 mm), robust, orange, red or brown; last two segments of antennae strongly enlarged in most males (Figs 1-2); frontal tubercles large, sub-quadratic; pronotum with antebasal transverse impression, limited on sides by short longitudinal furrows, and an additional longitudinal groove half way between short longitudinal furrows and lateral margin, running parallel to the lateral margin (Fig. 1); all pronotal margins bordered; procoxal cavities closed; apical ventrite trilobed in male, with internal anterior margin extended (Figs 7, 48 &amp; 49); and claws appendiculate.
</paragraph>
<caption id="8C5683F6235CD7C33190DD3ECAEA751A" pageId="1" pageNumber="80">
<paragraph id="8699CD932903B42957534C46086105E2" pageId="1" pageNumber="80">
Figures 1-2. 
<taxonomicName id="0334D7E3588C3CA03A1D044FEA70DF54" authority="Duvivier, 1891" authorityName="Duvivier" authorityYear="1891" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Sikkimia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Sikkimia rufa" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="80" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rufa">Sikkimia rufa</taxonomicName>
(Chen). 1 Male, dorsal view 2 Three apical antennomeres of right antenna, ventral view.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="0779778050FFA7D7A438B93DA3E8BDF0" pageId="1" pageNumber="80">
As all the main diagnostic characters are shared by both the continental and Taiwanese species, 
<taxonomicName id="B5DE1DE540A198F64C2C73B2A60E8824" authority="Kimoto, 1989" authorityName="Kimoto" authorityYear="1989" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Taiwanolepta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Taiwanolepta" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="80" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Taiwanolepta</taxonomicName>
is here synonymized with 
<taxonomicName id="95BDD151949D139CA70E5264623D25DD" authority="Duvivier, 1891" authorityName="Duvivier" authorityYear="1891" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Sikkimia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Sikkimia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="80" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Sikkimia</taxonomicName>
. Taiwanese species differ from the continental species in having a shorter body (6.1-9.0 mm) reduced hind wings and consequently reduced humeral calli. The apical antennomere in the male is spear-shaped and more or less symmetrical in continental species (Fig. 2, see also the drawings in 
<bibRefCitation id="421B10ABC5F38D925E9ABA24AF171124" author="Bezdek, J" journalOrPublisher="Genus" pageId="23" pageNumber="102" pagination="351 - 358" title="Yunomela Chen, 1964 and Vietocerus Lopatin, 2003, new synonyms of Sikkimia Duvivier, 1891 (Coleoptera: Chrysomelidae: Galerucinae)." volume="17" year="2006">
<normalizedToken id="8F9E4046E50C2FEE4DFB6DDB6970500D" originalValue="Bezděk">Bezdek</normalizedToken>
and Zhang (2006)
</bibRefCitation>
), while strongly asymmetrical in Taiwanese species (Figs 24-47). Outer longitudinal grooves on pronotum are deeper in Taiwanese species while more feeble in continental species. Aedeagus sclerotized ventrally in Taiwanese species, but membranous in continental species. Internal sclerite divergent apically in almost all Taiwanese species (Figs 19, 53, 66, 86), while the continental 
<taxonomicName id="0F5E562CABB0D02B2C29BC131690D656" authority="Duvivier, 1891" authorityName="Duvivier" authorityYear="1891" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Sikkimia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Sikkimia rufa" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="80" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rufa">Sikkimia rufa</taxonomicName>
has the sclerite divergent basally (Fig. 3). On the other hand, the structure of the spermatheca, gonocoxae, ventrite VIII and extended internal part of male abdominal ventrite V in the male are very similar (these structures of 
<taxonomicName id="1EEFA8DE3C06FA0501C5C8DCD3B74CA6" authority="Duvivier, 1891" authorityName="Duvivier" authorityYear="1891" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Sikkimia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Sikkimia rufa" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="80" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rufa">Sikkimia rufa</taxonomicName>
as in Figs 5-8, and for the other Taiwanese species as in Figs 21-23, 48, 49, 55-57, 68-70, 81-83).
</paragraph>
<caption id="C4DC5E6E721FC6D67A83CE982D663BB0" pageId="1" pageNumber="80">
<paragraph id="CDC72C01F7F7770B7E1FA7D2C3DF468E" pageId="1" pageNumber="80">
Figures 3-8. 
<taxonomicName id="E1216E56F9AA2E3369999098017144C1" authority="Duvivier, 1891" authorityName="Duvivier" authorityYear="1891" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Sikkimia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Sikkimia rufa" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="80" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rufa">Sikkimia rufa</taxonomicName>
(Chen). 3 Aedeagus, dorsal view 4 Aedeagus, lateral view 5 Apices of gonocoxae 6 Eigth abdominal ventrite 7 Male abdominal ventrites 
<normalizedToken id="BD765280C05502FF2A775CE55EC37AFA" originalValue="III–V">III-V</normalizedToken>
8 Spermatheca.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="B3B6C7B07DC265D195643901A684FB99" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="83" pageId="1" pageNumber="80" type="biology">
<paragraph id="CFB368C9204D440E8AB3920DB7AAEAC4" pageId="1" pageNumber="80">Biology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4B5307D8DE3A7BF8E51683E4EAE81B69" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="82" pageId="1" pageNumber="80">
Taiwanese species of 
<taxonomicName id="3B06820A75DC8938939BDA58C689AA56" authority="Duvivier, 1891" authorityName="Duvivier" authorityYear="1891" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Sikkimia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Sikkimia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="80" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Sikkimia</taxonomicName>
appear to be univoltine, based on field observations. Larvae are nocturnal and found on the underside of the host 
<normalizedToken id="48287FDE3E292C959C992B743125D766" originalValue="plant’s">plant's</normalizedToken>
leaves 
<pageBreakToken id="5E87C02955CE202BD49FA3AEA40516A2" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" start="start">between</pageBreakToken>
February and April. Larval development takes about 20-22 days, based on laboratory rearing. Mature larvae leave the host plant and burrow into the soil where they build underground chambers for pupation. The pupal stage lasts for 22 days, and adults begin to emerge after April. The adults are also nocturnal and live for more than 
<pageBreakToken id="8C4941E3545C3FC4DB3587BC92356111" pageId="3" pageNumber="82" start="start">three</pageBreakToken>
months, a lengthy longevity for chrysomelids. Females deposited single eggs on leaves under laboratory conditions, but these failed to hatch. Presumably 
<taxonomicName id="BAA2D0D75ADF9D3831AB5F4E796DE3F2" authority="Duvivier, 1891" authorityName="Duvivier" authorityYear="1891" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Sikkimia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Sikkimia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="82" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Sikkimia</taxonomicName>
species overwinter as adults, as some females were collected during winter.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F2BA0D6EB288B7EE0220F55CD0709A79" pageId="4" pageNumber="83">
<pageBreakToken id="AA36C842EFBC10ADDB0B8D56F503B167" pageId="4" pageNumber="83" start="start">All</pageBreakToken>
known 
<taxonomicName id="53FCA7CF066B2B99E6E0F3017FCA4C08" authority="Duvivier, 1891" authorityName="Duvivier" authorityYear="1891" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Sikkimia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Sikkimia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="83" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Sikkimia</taxonomicName>
species feed on the leaves of 
<taxonomicName id="89224C3862BE5CB66D58CD8534EBAECB" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polygonaceae" genus="Polygonum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Polygonum chinense" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="4" pageNumber="83" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="chinense">Polygonum chinense</taxonomicName>
L. (
<taxonomicName id="FDB46D8114F6E6AFFE739F95A07FE0E5" family="Polygonaceae" lsidName="" pageId="4" pageNumber="83" rank="family">Polygonaceae</taxonomicName>
) (Fig. 9). However, some populations of 
<taxonomicName id="DD0E06E729FCE9EA2F7F88C7E726EE8F" authority="Duvivier, 1891" authorityName="Duvivier" authorityYear="1891" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Sikkimia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Sikkimia tsoui" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="83" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tsoui">Sikkimia tsoui</taxonomicName>
sp. n. also feed on other plants in different areas. For example, populations from Yangminshan National Park (including Hsiaoyuken, Erhtzuping, Lengshuiken, Tatunshan) have been observed feeding on 
<taxonomicName id="DDF43DA601CE5A4929D14F5CCBF6D664" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Rubus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Rubus swinhoei" order="Rosales" pageId="4" pageNumber="83" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="swinhoei">Rubus swinhoei</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 15) and 
<taxonomicName id="1FB6FAC6290ABD59A823ACE35EA64897" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Rubus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Rubus corchorifolius" order="Rosales" pageId="4" pageNumber="83" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="corchorifolius">Rubus corchorifolius</taxonomicName>
