<paragraph id="DF9E6C20EB95812D939F8C2468B55688" pageId="4" pageNumber="83">
In Taiwan, leaf beetles from three genera are known to feed on 
<taxonomicName id="3D99FBE2DFD617DB02116F81BBDA93C7" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polygonaceae" genus="Polygonum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Polygonum chinense" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="4" pageNumber="83" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="chinense">Polygonum chinense</taxonomicName>
. These include 
<taxonomicName id="938386CDDF2833A75B373023CC9814F7" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Altica" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Altica birmanensis" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="83" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="birmanensis">Altica birmanensis</taxonomicName>
(Jacoby, 1896) (
<bibRefCitation id="2755E85267D2C89C5A82F1047E5AD29A" author="Lee, C-F" journalOrPublisher="Sishou-Hills Insect Observation Network Press, Taipei" pageId="23" pageNumber="102" title="The Chrysomelidae of Taiwan I." year="2007">Lee and Cheng 2007</bibRefCitation>
), 
<taxonomicName id="B24C403BF6FBB5F2427CB13693AD1BFE" authority="Motschoulsky, 1861" authorityName="Motschoulsky" authorityYear="1861" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Gallerucida" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Gallerucida singularis" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="83" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="singularis">Gallerucida singularis</taxonomicName>
Harold, 1880 (
<bibRefCitation id="BD268D4FDDEAC442AF498D9E9B215F9B" author="Lee, C-F" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="23" pageNumber="102" pagination="358 - 370" title="Revision of Gallerucidasingularis species group (Coleoptera: Chrysomelidae: Galerucinae)." url="10.11646/zootaxa.3647.2.7" volume="3647" year="2013">
Lee and 
<normalizedToken id="E3799EEC1429CC5508482918661E6A6B" originalValue="Bezděk">Bezdek</normalizedToken>
2013
</bibRefCitation>
), and 
<taxonomicName id="EAA2C8BCFCB398257A285BB63E7AD16C" authority="Duvivier, 1891" authorityName="Duvivier" authorityYear="1891" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Sikkimia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Sikkimia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="83" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Sikkimia</taxonomicName>
species. 
<taxonomicName id="7AB818216DFE14793415EE2C29E8526C" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Altica" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Altica birmanensis" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="83" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="birmanensis">Altica birmanensis</taxonomicName>
inhabits lowlands, at elevations below 1200 m. 
<taxonomicName id="ACA7A09A7A27146BC921F3ADE5C88333" authority="Motschoulsky, 1861" authorityName="Motschoulsky" authorityYear="1861" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Gallerucida" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Gallerucida singularis" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="83" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="singularis">Gallerucida singularis</taxonomicName>
occurs at slightly higher elevations, ranging between 1000 m and 1500 m. 
<taxonomicName id="809A82848A68F47A5FF30A28741FD89D" authority="Duvivier, 1891" authorityName="Duvivier" authorityYear="1891" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Sikkimia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Sikkimia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="83" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Sikkimia</taxonomicName>
species occupy the higher elevations, and are found from 1000 m to 2500 m in central and southern Taiwan. Thus 
<taxonomicName id="E297693AC85948D522E3F9DABC780FE6" authority="Motschoulsky, 1861" authorityName="Motschoulsky" authorityYear="1861" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Gallerucida" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Gallerucida singularis" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="83" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="singularis">Gallerucida singularis</taxonomicName>
is sympatric with 
<taxonomicName id="F22F5E0ED52651B44B1B321FB89A9206" authority="Duvivier, 1891" authorityName="Duvivier" authorityYear="1891" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Sikkimia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Sikkimia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="83" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Sikkimia</taxonomicName>
species in some areas. Although members of both taxa are nocturnal, their larvae prefer different sites on the host plant. Larvae of 
<taxonomicName id="8B6AA32BDA4ACCB57C4417D654962876" authority="Motschoulsky, 1861" authorityName="Motschoulsky" authorityYear="1861" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Gallerucida" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Gallerucida singularis" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="83" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="singularis">Gallerucida singularis</taxonomicName>
always appear on the upper surface of leaves, their body segments lack lateral expansions, and the apical posterior tergites are narrower (Fig. 12). 
<taxonomicName id="A20C6552387D61D61F95C632838C8B47" authority="Duvivier, 1891" authorityName="Duvivier" authorityYear="1891" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Sikkimia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Sikkimia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="83" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Sikkimia</taxonomicName>
larvae occur on the underside of leaves, each body segment has lateral expansions, and the apical posterior tergites are wider (Figs 9-11).
</paragraph>
